While ''The Sun'' claimed &quot;150,000 of New York City's Most Influential Readers Every Day&quot;, ''The Sun''{{'}}s own audit indicated that it was selling approximately 14,000 copies a day—while giving away between 66,000 and 85,000 a day.&lt;ref name=&quot;wapo-cross&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Sherman&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;nyt-cross&quot;&gt;{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/21/nyregion/22sun.html?sq=&amp;st=cse&amp;%2334;new%20york%20sun=&amp;%2334;=&amp;scp=9&amp;pagewanted=all | title=After 6 Years, N.Y. Sun Finds Itself at a Crossroads | author=Barron, James | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 21, 2008 | access-date=February 18, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220055703/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/21/nyregion/22sun.html?sq=&amp;st=cse&amp;%2334;new%20york%20sun=&amp;%2334;=&amp;scp=9&amp;pagewanted=all | archive-date=December 20, 2016 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all | author-link=James Barron (journalist) }}&lt;/ref&gt; (The New York ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]'' sold about 700,000 copies a day during that period.) It offered free subscriptions for a full year to residents in advertiser-desired zip codes;&lt;ref name=&quot;Sherman&quot;/&gt; this and other uses of [[controlled circulation]] made it more attractive to advertisers, but further diminished its chances of ever becoming profitable.&lt;ref name=&quot;nyt-cross&quot;/&gt;
Similarly, ''The Sun''{{'}}s online edition was accessible for free since August 2006.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
 |url          = http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlny/newspapers/new_york_sun_sees_light_makes_web_free_41612.asp
 |title        = New York Sun Sees Light, Makes Web Free
 |date         = August 8, 2006
 |publisher    = mediabistro.com
 |accessdate   = 2008-02-04
 |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930210054/https://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlny/newspapers/new_york_sun_sees_light_makes_web_free_41612.asp
 |archive-date = September 30, 2007
 |url-status   = dead
 |df           = mdy-all
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

''The Sun'' acquired the web address www.LatestPolitics.com in 2007.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.mediainfo.com/eandp/departments/online/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003584849 (requires registration to access)] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In a letter to readers published on the front page of the September 4, 2008, edition, Lipsky announced that the paper had suffered substantial losses and would &quot;cease publication at the end of September unless we succeed in our efforts to find additional financial backing.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news
 |url          = http://www.nysun.com/editorials/the-future-of-the-sun/85129/
 |title        = The Future of the Sun
 |date         = September 4, 2008
 |author       = Seth Lipsky
 |newspaper    = The New York Sun
 |accessdate   = 2008-09-04
 |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080904083327/http://www.nysun.com/editorials/the-future-of-the-sun/85129/
 |archive-date = September 4, 2008
 |url-status     = live
 |df           = mdy-all
}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=nyt20080904&gt;Perez-Pena, Richard (September 4, 2008), [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/04/nyregion/04sun.html New York Sun May Close if Millions Aren't Found] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220054459/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/04/nyregion/04sun.html |date=2016-12-20 }}. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved on September 4, 2008.&lt;/ref&gt; In particular, the paper's existing backers would not put forward more money unless new backers with capital were found.&lt;ref name=&quot;wapo-cross&quot;/&gt; The chance that funding had of materializing was negated by the onset of the [[financial crisis of 2007–2008]], and ''The Sun'' ceased publication on September 30, 2008.&lt;ref name=&quot;ap-end&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;end&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;nyt-end&quot;/&gt; It had approximately 110 employees at that time,&lt;ref name=&quot;nyt-end&quot;&gt;{{cite news | url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2008/09/30/losing-money-new-york-sun-is-to-shut-down-after-6-years/ | title=New York Sun to Shut Down | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 30, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623162054/http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2008/09/30/losing-money-new-york-sun-is-to-shut-down-after-6-years/?scp=6&amp;sq=%22new%20york%20sun%22&amp;st=cse | archive-date=June 23, 2015 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}&lt;/ref&gt; and also made use of many [[freelance writer]]s.&lt;ref name=&quot;wapo-cross&quot;/&gt; Mayor of New York [[Michael Bloomberg]] commented that &quot;The Sun shone brightly, though too briefly,&quot; and that its writers were &quot;smart, thoughtful, provocative&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;nyt-end&quot;/&gt;

==Online version 2009–present==
Despite the closure of the newspaper, ''The New York Sun'' website renewed activity on April 28, 2009,&lt;ref name=&quot;Klonick04282009&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |first=Seth |last=Lipsky |authorlink=Seth Lipsky |title=Sound Familiar? |date=April 28, 2009 |url=http://www.nysun.com/editorials/sound-familiar/86869/ |work=The New York Sun |accessdate=July 18, 2010 |quote=Our own view is that Mr. Cheney just might have beaten Mr. Obama, ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618034753/http://www.nysun.com/editorials/sound-familiar/86869/ |archive-date=June 18, 2010 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}&lt;/ref&gt; prompting some observers to consider the possible implications.&lt;ref name=&quot;Klonick04282009&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Seward04292009&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.niemanlab.org/2009/04/is-that-the-defunct-new-york-sun-peeking-over-the-digital-horizon/ |title=Is that the defunct New York Sun peeking over the digital horizon? |author=Zachary M. Seward |date=April 29, 2009 |work=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism|Nieman Journalism Lab]] |accessdate=July 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516222612/http://www.niemanlab.org/2009/04/is-that-the-defunct-new-york-sun-peeking-over-the-digital-horizon/ |archive-date=May 16, 2010 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Calderone04292009&quot; /&gt; Michael Calderone of ''[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]'' quoted Lipsky as saying not to read too much into the initial items since &quot;...a business plan for the site is still in formation,&quot; and &quot;... these are just some very, very early bulbs of spring (or late winter).&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;Calderone04292009&quot;&gt;{{cite news |title=N.Y. Sun considers business plan for site |first=Michael |last=Calderone |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/michaelcalderone/0409/NY_Sun_considers_business_model_for_site_.html?showall |newspaper=[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]] |publisher=Robert L. Allbritton |location=Arlington, VA |date=April 29, 2009 |accessdate=July 17, 2010 |quote=The New York Sun, which closed up shop in September, has been publishing a bit lately online, ... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516042651/http://www.politico.com/blogs/michaelcalderone/0409/NY_Sun_considers_business_model_for_site_.html?showall |archive-date=May 16, 2010 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Since that time, the web site has continued to publish editorials at irregular intervals,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.nysun.com/op-ed/ |title=Editorials/Opinion |work=The New York Sun |publisher=[[Seth Lipsky]] |accessdate=July 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817101427/http://www.nysun.com/op-ed |archive-date=August 17, 2010 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}&lt;/ref&gt; op-ed commentaries&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.nysun.com/opinion/ |title=The New York Sun, Opinion |author=various authors |publisher=Seth Lipsky |accessdate=July 11, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708053849/http://www.nysun.com/opinion/ |archive-date=July 8, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}&lt;/ref&gt; and frequent contributions from economist and noted television commentator [[Lawrence Kudlow]]. In addition, commentaries on the arts have been published.

==Related publication==
===''CityArts''===
In March 2009, a group of former contributors to ''The Sun''{{'}}s arts section, including Lance Esplund, [[Brice Brown]], Jay Nordlinger, Joel Lobenthal, and Marion Maneker, spearheaded a new paper, ''CityArts'', published by [[Manhattan Media]]. ''CityArts'' began as a monthly arts supplement in other Manhattan Media papers (including ''[[New York Press]]'', ''West Side Spirit'', and ''Our Town''), but soon changed to a stand-alone, twice-monthly free publication. A notice from 2009 claimed a distribution of 50,000 print copies.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.manhattanmedia.com/press.php] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121123050115/http://manhattanmedia.com/press.php |date=2012-11-23 }}. Accessed 24 October 2012.&lt;/ref&gt; The paper's contents were published online at cityarts.info.

Due to low advertising revenue, ''CityArts'' reverted to a supplement in late 2012.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |author=Howard Mandel |url=http://www.artsjournal.com/jazzbeyondjazz/2012/09/demise-er-downsizing-of-an-new-york-city-arts-review.html |title=Demise — er, downsizing — of a New York City arts review |publisher=Artsjournal.com |date=2012-09-13 |accessdate=2014-07-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720041743/http://www.artsjournal.com/jazzbeyondjazz/2012/09/demise-er-downsizing-of-an-new-york-city-arts-review.html |archive-date=2014-07-20 |url-status=live }}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Controversies==
Allegations published in the paper's January 9, 2008 issue, written by [[contributing editor]] [[Daniel Johnson (journalist)|Daniel Johnson]] about then-candidate [[Barack Obama]] and Kenya's candidate (and subsequent Prime Minister) [[Raila Odinga]], based on what was later described as &quot;a patently fallacious story ... or at the very least to shirk their responsibility to the truth.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
   |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/joel-whitney/the-inew-york-sunis-obama_b_118785.html
   |title=The New York Sun's Obama Frame-Up
   |author=Joel Whitney  |date=August 16, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite magazine
|magazine=Guernica Magazine
|url=http://www.guernicamag.com/blog/612/obama_and_the_kenya_deception
|title=Obama and the Kenya Deception
|author=Joel Whitney
|date=
|access-date=August 6, 2008
